				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The growth in EU SMP exports appear to have peaked, and non-ACP markets are the primary focus for EU exports. But the scale of EU exports – which have increased more than threefold since 2008 – means that the EU export trade still has the potential to play a major role, selling SMP as a feedstock for expanded UHT production or dried milk distribution targeting African markets.</p><p>In Eastern and Southern Africa, where a well-established dairy sector exists, the projected growth in consumer demand for UHT milk will raise a range of concerns related to the trade policy framework for the use of imported milk powders in meeting expanding consumer demand for dairy products (especially liquid milk), as well as raising policy issues related to intra-regional trade in liquid milk. Illustrative of this is the situation in Namibia. At the beginning of November 2013, milk shortages were reported, following the introduction of import restrictions on dairy products in response to a request for protection from the local Dairy Producers Association. The situation was compounded by the drought conditions in Namibia, which prompted increased purchases of fodder, raising production costs.</p><p>This needs to be seen against the background of corporate policies in South Africa that have successfully integrated imported milk powders into the production of value-added dairy products for export to African markets (see <i>Agritrade</i>
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Executive-Brief-Update-2013-Dairy-sector" target="_blank">Executive Brief Update 2013: ‘Dairy sector</a>’, 18 December 2013 and <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Trends-in-South-Africa-dairy-trade-highlighted" target="_blank">Trends in South African dairy trade highlighted</a>’,18 March 2013).</p>
		</div>
		
